		<div class="lia-message-body lia-component-body" id="messagebodydisplay_0" class="lia-message-body">
	
		<div class="lia-message-body-content">
			
                
                    <BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE border="1"><TBODY><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><DIV><IMG src="http://cache.LEGO.com/images/forums/en-US/icon-quote.gif" /> <STRONG>IMOK2 wrote:</STRONG></DIV><DIV class="quoteTable"><BLOCKQUOTE><DIV><IMG src="http://cache.LEGO.com/images/forums/en-US/icon-quote.gif" /> <STRONG>ellimist2 wrote:</STRONG></DIV><DIV class="quoteTable">&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;div&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;I want to be about 6 feet, have blackish brown windblown hair, carry a gun that comes up to my elbow, like Samus Aran's gun, and a blade that has lots of blue techno wires up it.<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;I want to wear sliver shoulder armor and brown and silver robes with a small amount of armor on my body, and matching armored boots.<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;That's all, hope it wasn't too long!<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;ASSEMBLY FOREVER!!!!<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;ThatchGears  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Yes, everyone mentioned in the previous book will be in the new one! <BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;Hurricane, a few posts back, you had asked why Duke Exeter was evil. Well, I have the answer for you now:<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;"There is no good or evil, but thinking makes it so."<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;William Shakespeare wrote that, or something along those lines, in Hamlet. (LOL, I just looked up on the internet a couple of days ago.)<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;So, what he means is that there is no good or evil. But, whatever way you think makes it good or evil.<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;-Formic<BR /><BR />&lt;br/&gt;-Milligan in game &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;br/&gt;some say there is ma'at (order) and chaos. (read about that in the red pyramid)</DIV></BLOCKQUOTE>&lt;br/&gt;classic modern-fantasy alignment (like that) has two groups of polar oposites, they are<BR /><BR />good-evil<BR /><BR />and<BR /><BR />law-chaos<BR /><BR />while the good/evil and order/chaos are mutually exclusive, you can be good and order/good and chaos, or evil and order/ evil and chaos.<BR /><BR />and there is neutrality, neutral good, neutral evil, neutral law, and neutral chaos, which mean you are just good, or just evil, or just order, or whatever.<BR /><BR />and true neutrality, but that is near-impossible to be fully neutral<BR /><BR /><BR /><BR />yeah, im a nerd.<IMG src="/html/images/emoticons/emotion-15.gif" alt="[8-|]" /><BR /><BR /> </DIV></BLOCKQUOTE>&lt;br/&gt;Actually, I made up an alternate universe today where minifigs had to escape from their galaxy eons ago, and they journeyed through deep space for dozens of generations. Over this time, they mentally regressed, becoming somewhat like Rabbids in terms of average intelligence and attention span, if anyone has ever played one of those video games. The first to reach a new galaxy was a ship containing minifigs that kept their original intelligence but were mutated into horrible monstrosities with deformed skin [known to some as flesh-colored minifigs], and they became bitter and evil. The new galaxy was populated by clone-brand figures, devoted to utterly imagination-less law and order, and the fleshies joined them. However, the yellow figs still carried imagination with them, and they mercilessly smashed all who opposed it, driving the few survivors far beyond the outer rim.<BR /><BR /><BR /><BR />Now, it isn't about good versus evil. It's about order versus chaos, and order, I'm glad to say, is fighting a losing battle. This is a universe of parodies and paradoxes, parachutes and parakeets, paratroopers and paralegals! The minifigs may seem like peaceful little fellows, but that smiling face contains the heart of a violent, merciless warrior. Now, you may be thinking that it is because of some deep-seated grudge against life itself, but the truth is, these minifigs just love blowing each other up, and love being blown up themselves almost as much, because they realize just how awesome it is. They exist to spread destruction, awesomeness, and humor, and wars are always being fought over whatever seems to be the funniest possible cause. The minifigs share a proud heritage of fighting in primordial toy boxes, where they weren't subject to the mundane laws of logic, physics, and continuity, so why should they be now? Furthermore, the entire universe is like a crazy, pun-filled parody of the universe [for example, did you know that the great Master Yo-yo created a strange type of energy called the "fork" out of mini-chlorines, and that its dark side is called the "spork"] It is said in ancient legend that somewhere within this universe exists a mythical place known only as the Amazing Brick Source [ABS, like the type of plastic that LEGO uses], where all LEGO pieces are made. Due to the massive amount of Imagination that it produces, great cities can be built in mere days. However, they're usually destroyed just as quickly, and if, for some reason, the enemy fails to do so, the minifigs of the city will generally get bored quickly and smash it themselves so that they can build something else. Because of this great imaginative force, the most valuable things are bricks. Some minifigs are part of great empires spanning dozens of planets, while others eke out an existence on forsaken pieces of rock in space salvaging for bricks and often resorting to "rainbow-ism" for their creations. Due to their incredibly short attention-span, there are very few civilians in this universe. The minifgs are generally only satisfied when doing things such as fighting to the death, discovering ancient treasures, and building incredible fortresses, powerful starships, and weapons of mass destruction. And now... I've been holding it back... <IMG src="/html/images/emoticons/emotion-4.gif" alt="Stick out tongue" /><IMG src="/html/images/emoticons/emotion-4.gif" alt="Stick out tongue" /><IMG src="/html/images/emoticons/emotion-4.gif" alt="Stick out tongue" />!!!<BR /><BR /><BR /><BR />-Emperorfred </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><BR />Yay, I'm a craftsman!!! Although, I DID like the Master Builder icon better...<BR /><BR />-Emperorfred, COG supporter and Assembly member<BR /><BR />"As they say in the produce aisle, lettuce begin."<BR />
                
            
			
				<div style="width:98%; max-height:100px; overflow:hidden;" class="UserSignature lia-message-signature">
	-Jones<BR /><BR />"Before you criticize a man, you should always walk a mile in his shoes. That way, when you criticize him, you're a mile away and you have his shoes."
</div>
			
			
